<tr>
  <td class="diff-marker">−</td>
  <td class="diff-deletedline"><div>In an age before steam power, the wilderness that would become Ancaster had an early economic advantage due to the fact that it existed<del class="diffchange diffchange-inline"> naturally</del> amidst a break in the [[Niagara Escarpment]]. Thus even its relatively minor water resources were valuable because they were easily accessible. Just as vital an influence in Ancaster's rapid development was the fact that it already had access to two very important prehistoric [[First Nations]] roads<del class="diffchange diffchange-inline">. In other words the successful settlement that would become Ancaster wasn't entirely by chance</del>. The first European settlers to set foot in this region would have encountered the Iroquois Trail and the [[Mohawk Road (Hamilton, Ontario)|Mohawk Trail]] intersecting precisely in the area that would eventually become Ancaster Village. This aboriginal Iroquois trail had become the most important transportation route in Upper Canada. It meandered down the escarpment from the future Ancaster into what would eventually become Hamilton, Ontario towards present day [[Lewiston, New York]], eventually linking up with similar aboriginal trails in [[New York]]. In the other direction the Iroquois trail led from present day Ancaster to what would eventually become the town of [[Brantford|Brantford, Ontario]] whereupon the trail then branched off into the Detroit Path and the Long Point trail. By 1770, the 80 kilometre Mohawk Trail was essentially the escarpment accompaniment of the lakeside Iroquois trail. The Mohawk Trail ran parallel to the Iroquois trail and originated and diverged from the Iroquois trail in present day [[Queenston, Ontario]] until finally ending and reconnecting to the Iroquois Trail in present day Ancaster at what is now known as the intersection of Rousseaux and Wilson Street. The two trails actually interconnected in four locations along the Mohawk Trail's 80 kilometre route when favourable escarpment conditions permitted. By 1785, the Iroquois Trail passing through present day Ancaster had been widened to accommodate horse and buggy traffic. Another influential road that intersected the Mohawk Trail very close to Ancaster Village was the Twenty Mile road that followed the [[Twenty Mile Creek]] up to present day [[Smithville, Ontario]] and beyond.&lt;ref name="The Niagara Peninsula 1851"&gt;The Origin And Development Of The Road Network Of The Niagara Peninsula, Ontario, 1770-1851. Andrew F. Burghardt McMaster University, Hamilton, Ontario&lt;/ref&gt; Lastly, Ancaster also had fertile soil and abundant fresh water which encouraged pioneer settlers to arrive in this region to clear the land and plant crops for subsistence [[agriculture]].</div></td>
  <td class="diff-marker">+</td>
  <td class="diff-addedline"><div>In an age before steam power, the wilderness that would become Ancaster had an early economic advantage due to the fact that it existed amidst a<ins class="diffchange diffchange-inline"> natural</ins> break in the [[Niagara Escarpment]]. Thus even its relatively minor water resources were valuable because they were easily accessible. Just as vital an influence in Ancaster's rapid development was the fact that it already had access to two very important prehistoric [[First Nations]] roads. The first European settlers to set foot in this region would have encountered the Iroquois Trail and the [[Mohawk Road (Hamilton, Ontario)|Mohawk Trail]] intersecting precisely in the area that would eventually become Ancaster Village. This aboriginal Iroquois trail had become the most important transportation route in Upper Canada. It meandered down the escarpment from the future Ancaster into what would eventually become Hamilton, Ontario towards present day [[Lewiston, New York]], eventually linking up with similar aboriginal trails in [[New York]]. In the other direction the Iroquois trail led from present day Ancaster to what would eventually become the town of [[Brantford|Brantford, Ontario]] whereupon the trail then branched off into the Detroit Path and the Long Point trail. By 1770, the 80 kilometre Mohawk Trail was essentially the escarpment accompaniment of the lakeside Iroquois trail. The Mohawk Trail ran parallel to the Iroquois trail and originated and diverged from the Iroquois trail in present day [[Queenston, Ontario]] until finally ending and reconnecting to the Iroquois Trail in present day Ancaster at what is now known as the intersection of Rousseaux and Wilson Street. The two trails actually interconnected in four locations along the Mohawk Trail's 80 kilometre route when favourable escarpment conditions permitted. By 1785, the Iroquois Trail passing through present day Ancaster had been widened to accommodate horse and buggy traffic. Another influential road that intersected the Mohawk Trail very close to Ancaster Village was the Twenty Mile road that followed the [[Twenty Mile Creek]] up to present day [[Smithville, Ontario]] and beyond.&lt;ref name="The Niagara Peninsula 1851"&gt;The Origin And Development Of The Road Network Of The Niagara Peninsula, Ontario, 1770-1851. Andrew F. Burghardt McMaster University, Hamilton, Ontario&lt;/ref&gt; Lastly, Ancaster also had fertile soil and abundant fresh water which encouraged pioneer settlers to arrive in this region to clear the land and plant crops for subsistence [[agriculture]].</div></td>
</tr>
